did.abstract:
Portraits of individuals from other communities and locales include street portraits of pedestrians in New York City; residents of a drug rehabilitation program at facilities throughout New York State; the people of Heber Springs, Arkansas, the rural town photographed decades earlier by Mike Disfarmer; and African American members of the First Baptist Church of Riverhead, New York. Tucker's commission work includes portraits of individuals, couples, and families. Her personal photography projects include portraits of family members, friends, and bodybuilders, as well as seascape and landscape photography.
The subjects for Tucker's portraiture have come principally from Native American populations. These include members of the Onondaga Nation, Shinnecock Indian Nation, Navajo Nation, and Montaukett Indians. Tucker has also documented Native American artists from pueblos throughout the southwestern United States.
This collection documents the career of Toba Pato Tucker as a portrait photographer, circa 1950-2011, and landscape photography since 2010, with the bulk of the collection from 1977 to 2015. The photographic materials in this collection consist of exhibition prints, work prints, and negatives for nine major projects, as well as her commission work and personal photography. The papers largely support her photographic work and consist of her project files, which include background research, correspondence, and oral history interviews. The papers also include exhibition catalogs, publications, and publicity material produced for projects, as well as a small amount of personal papers.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: During her lifetime, Toba Pato Tucker retains any and all copyrights she holds in the Toba Pato Tucker Photographs and Papers collection and full authority to control commercial use of materials in it. On her death, any copyrights she holds in the collection will transfer to Yale University.

During the lifetime of Ms. Tucker, the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library has the limited right to grant permission for no more than three of her photographs for reproduction in what it deems a scholarly publication. Individuals applying for such permission shall specify the publication in which the images will appear and pay Toba Pato Tucker $25 per published photograph for one-time, non-exclusive reproduction rights. All reproductions must include the complete original image without any cropping. The reproductions must also credit Toba Pato Tucker and have an accompanying statement indicating that she holds copyright. For further information, consult the Curator of the Yale Collection of Western Americana.

processinfo.p: Exhibition prints in the collection are individually described based on language provided by Tucker. The titles for individual projects derive from names given by Tucker.

bioghist.head: Toba Pato Tucker (born 1935)
bioghist.p: Toba Pato Tucker refers to herself as "a contemporary American documentary portrait photographer" who "strives to record continuity and change in American culture for history and artistic purposes with a particular interest in Native American populations."

Born and raised in the Bronx, New York, Toba Pato married Robert Paul Tucker (Yale 1944) in 1956. They, and their daughter, Dena Suzanne Tucker, lived in West Hartford, Connecticut. After the marriage ended, Toba Pato Tucker returned to New York City.

Initially a self-taught amateur photographer, Tucker began her professional career after attending a workshop taught by Harold Feinstein in 1976. In her early work, she used a Pentax camera that exposed thirty-five millimeter film. In 1976, she bought a used Hasselblad camera that exposed 120 millimeter film. The following year her friend and mentor Toby Old helped her master the intricacies of the Hasselblad as well as how to develop black and white film and print fine art silver gelatin photographs. Although Tucker occasionally used other cameras, the Hasselblad was her primary camera for the remainder of her career. Primarily a black and white photographer, Tucker occasionally used color negative film. From 1978 to 1980, she taught at the International Center of Photography in New York City.

Over her career, the subjects for her portraiture have chiefly come from Native American populations. These include members of the Onondaga Nation, Shinnecock Indian Nation, Navajo Nation, and Montaukett Indians. Tucker has also documented Native American artists from pueblos throughout the southwestern United States.

Tucker also created portraits of individuals from other communities and locales, including street portraits of pedestrians in New York City and Minneapolis, Minnesota; residents of Day Top Village, a drug rehabilitation program with facilities throughout New York State; the people of Heber Springs, Arkansas -- the rural town photographed decades earlier by Mike Disfarmer (1884-1959); and African American members of the First Baptist Church of Riverhead, New York. During her work with residents of Day Top Village and Heber Springs, Tucker taped oral history interviews with her portrait subjects.
In 2012, Tucker began concentrating on landscape photography, epitomized by a project to document the American West using the work of nineteenth century photographers as reference points.

In her commission work, Tucker created portraits of individuals, couples, and families. Other projects included portraits of family members, friends, and bodybuilders, as well as seascape and landscape photography.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection documents the photographic career of Toba Pato Tucker, including her various photographic projects. These projects include:

list.item: Street Portraits (1977): Portraits of people on the street in New York City and Minneapolis.
Daytop Village Portraits (1977-1980): Portraits of residents of a therapeutic drug rehabilitation program with facilities throughout New York State.

Navajo Portraits (1981): Portraits of Navajo people living in Navajo-Hopi Joint Use Area, also known as Black Mesa or Big Mountain in Navajo County, Arizona, during which project she also made landscape photographs of the Navajo Reservation.
Shinnecock Indians of Eastern Long Island (1984-1987): Portraits of a multi-racial Native American reservation located on the east side of Shinnecock Bay in Southampton, Long Island, New York.
Black History & Folklife Project, Riverhead, New York (1986): Portraits of African American members the First Baptist Church of Riverhead, New York.
Heber Springs Portraits (1989-1991): Portraits of residents of a rural Arkansas town, which consciously revisited the subject matter photographed decades earlier by Mike Disfarmer (1884-1959).

Haudenosaunee, Portraits of the Firekeepers, The Onondaga Nation (1991-1992): Portraits of tribal members on the Onondaga Reservation in upstate New York, as well as landscapes showing community buildings.
Pueblo Artists, Portraits (1995-1997): Photographs of Native American artists and their families from pueblos throughout Arizona and New Mexico.
Native American Relocation Project (2001): Portraits of Native Americans whose families moved to southern California under programs sponsored by the federal government in the 1950s.
Re Viewing the American Landscape, West & Southwest (2012-): Landscape photography of the American West that references the work of nineteenth century photographers.

scopecontent.p: Additional material in this collection also documents several smaller projects, which include:

list.item: The Urban Indian (1980): Portraits from the Native American Center, Los Angeles, California.
Portraits of the Montaukett Indians of eastern Long Island (1986 and 1988).
Portraits of amateur bodybuilders in Southampton, Long Island (1986-1987).
Landscapes of Abiquiu Lake, New Mexico (2003).

scopecontent.p: The collections also documents personal portraits, landscapes, and seascapes Tucker has made throughout her career as well as commissioned portraits she made between 1980 and 2003.

The photographic materials in the collection consist of exhibition prints, work prints, and negatives for Tucker's various projects, as well as her commissioned work and personal photographs. Her project files include background research, correspondence, and interviews. The collection includes exhibition catalogs, publications, and publicity material produced by projects as well as a small quantity of her personal papers.

Many photographs of Native Americans in the collection document these individuals and their communities during the late twentieth century. Most of the portraits depict Native Americans wearing modern clothes, which underscore their contemporary lives. Portraits of individuals wearing traditional costumes also appear throughout the collection, reflect Tucker's interest in tracing cultural continuity as well as change within Native American communities.

The photographs and papers for the Daytop Village Portraits project provide unique documentation of drug rehabilitation centers during the 1970s. The audio interviews frequently report the circumstances of individuals that led them to drug use and of their eventual entry into the rehabilitation center, while other audio recordings provide glimpses into the program from the residents' vantage point.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into four series: I. Photographs, circa 1970-2003. II. Project Files, circa 1950-2005. III. Personal and Professional Papers, circa 1965-2006. IV. Additions 2008-2011, 1995-2011. V. Re Viewing the American Landscape West & Southwest , 2012-2015.

arrangement.p: Series I is organized into four subseries: Exhibition Prints, Work Prints, Negatives and Contact Sheets, and Color Slides.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series I mainly consists of photographic materials created by Tucker during her projects, as well as her commissioned portraits and personal portraits. The photographic material documents the evolution of images from negatives captured during portrait sessions through their development into exhibition prints. The negatives show variant images captured by Tucker of subjects, while the related work prints, contact sheets, and negatives frequently include her notes for printing exhibition prints. The exhibition prints relay her final vision for the each image. Most of the photographic prints are black and white, usually with a square frame, although she included color photographic materials in a few projects, including the Navajo Portraits and the Onondaga Nation Portraits. Tucker rarely crops her images and her prints usually show the entire image captured in her negatives.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged by the size of the photographic prints under four headings: 8 inches by 10 inches or smaller; 11 inches by 14 inches; 16 inches by 20 inches; 20 inches by 24 inches. Within each size, prints are arranged by projects (Day Top Village Portraits, Navajo Portraits; Shinnecock Indians of Eastern Long Island; Riverhead; Heber Springs Portraits; Onondaga Nation Portraits; Pueblo Artists, Portraits; Urban Indians in Southern Galifornia) followed by Commmission Work, Additional Projects, Personal Portraits, Photographs of Toba Tucker by Other Photographers, Portraits of Toba Tucker by Daytop Village Residents, and Photographs by Others Collected by Toba Tucker. Some categories are represented in all three sizes of photographic prints; others are represented in one or two sizes.

Within the categories, prints are arranged chronologically by date of creation except for Photographs of Toba Tucker by Other Photographers and Photographs by Others Collected by Toba Tucker which are organized alphabetically by the creator's last name.
Color work, where it exists, has been listed separately for each project, following the chronological arrangement of black and white prints.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries consists of exhibition prints that usually became Tucker's final product of a particular image or became the basis for reproductions in her publications.

The subseries also includes portraits of Tucker created by other photographers, including portraits of her created by residents of the Daytop Village drug rehabilitation center and work by other photographers collected by Tucker.

A small selection of photographs are present in Series II, Project Files, in the subseries documenting the Heber Springs Portraits, and consist of original photographs and copies of photographs created by Mike Disfarmer, as well as her personal informal photographs related to the project. Examples of publications that reproduced her photographs are present in Series III, Personal and Professional Papers, in the subseries, Publications that Include Images by Tucker.
Each folder in the 11 inches by 14 inches and 16 by 20 inches subseries contains a single photographic print.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Series II is organized into twelve subseries: Daytop Village Portraits, Navajo Portraits, Black History & Folklife Project, Riverhead, New York, Shinnecock Indians of Eastern Long Island, Heber Springs Portraits, Onondaga Nation Portraits, Pueblo Artists, Portraits, Native American Relocation Project, Commissioned Portraits, Additional Projects, Personal Portraits, and Oversize.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series II includes textual and audiovisual materials compiled by Tucker for each of her photographic projects. The largest documentation is available for the Daytop Village Portraits and Heber Springs Portraits. The files document the course of each project and include background research on the community and correspondence with portrait subjects, scholars, or funding institutions. Audiotapes in several of the project files contain interviews conducted by Tucker with portrait subjects and subject experts, including anthropologists, historians, and sociologists. The interviews often include biographical information about the portrait subjects or information about their community. A few audiotapes document telephone conversations of Tucker. Portrait lists and release forms identify portrait subjects. These project files also contain information about the products of a project, including exhibition catalogs (including publicity materials explicitly produced for the exhibitions), publications, and other publicity material.

unittitle.title: Re Viewing the American Landscape West & Southwest

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series V includes landscape photography by Tucker, 2012-2015, from her ongoing project, Re Viewing the American Landscape, West & Southwest , that references the work of nineteenth century photographers in her visual documentation of the American West

Inkjet prints have printed titles on rectos. In her titles, Tucker uses a swung dash mark to separate phrases in her titles. Due to limitations of typescript expression in computer systems, this guide substitutes dashes for the swung dashes. Additionally, the printed titles are prefixed with locations, which this guide transmits as subseries. Subseries titles are also informed by interleaving sheets between groups of prints when accessioned by the Library. The interleaving sheets are retained in the collection.
Occassionally this guide expands abbreviations in print titles. All captialization in the titles are by Tucker.
Each inkjet print of an image created by Tucker is signed a dated by her on versos.
